    "actor_description": "I don't realize I'm crying until my throat tightens and my eyes burn. It isn't sadness-it's the opposite: the sudden, almost embarrassing pressure of having been met when I expected to fend for myself. My chest feels too full, like my body is trying to make room for what I can't say cleanly. I blink hard. I breathe in, and it trembles on the way out. I want to speak, to name it, but the gratitude keeps arriving faster than language.",
    "description_text": "{actor} goes still in a way that isn't blank-more like holding something carefully. Their eyes shine; they blink more than they need to. When they inhale, their breath catches, and their mouth presses into a fragile line that keeps trying to become a smile. If they speak, the first word threatens to break.",
    "alternate_descriptions": {
        "auditory": "I hear a breath hitch-then a soft exhale that doesn't quite steady. Words start and stop, swallowed and tried again, as if the speaker is fighting not to cry while still needing to say thank you."
    },
